item: { flexDirection: "row", justifyContent: "space-between", padding: 10, borderBottomWidth: 1, borderBottomColor: "#ccc", } rewrite as tailwind

Sure, here's the equivalent styling using Tailwind CSS:

html
<div class="flex flex-row justify-between p-2.5 border-b border-gray-300">
  <!-- Your content here -->
</div>

Explanation:

  • flex flex-row: Sets the element to a flex container with row direction.
  • justify-between: Distributes space between items.
  • p-2.5: Adds padding of 10px (2.5 * 4px = 10px).
  • border-b: Adds a bottom border.
  • border-gray-300: Sets the border color to a light gray (#ccc).
input: { borderWidth: 1, borderColor: "#000", padding: 10, marginBottom: 10, }

Here's the equivalent styling using Tailwind CSS:

html
<input class="border border-black p-2.5 mb-2.5">

Explanation:

  • border: Adds a border with the default width of 1px.
  • border-black: Sets the border color to black.
  • p-2.5: Adds padding of 10px (2.5 * 4px = 10px).
  • mb-2.5: Adds a margin-bottom of 10px (2.5 * 4px = 10px).
headerImage: { width: "100%", height: 200, }

Here's the equivalent styling using Tailwind CSS:

html
<img class="w-full h-50">

Explanation:

  • w-full: Sets the width to 100%.
  • h-50: Sets the height to 200 pixels. (Tailwind uses multiples of 4 pixels for spacing utilities, so h-50 equals 200px, because 50 * 4px = 200px).

If you don't have custom heights in your Tailwind configuration, you can define the height using inline style or extend Tailwind's configuration:

Using inline style:

html
<img class="w-full" style="height: 200px;">

Extending Tailwind configuration (tailwind.config.js):

js
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      height: {
        '200': '200px',
      },
    },
  },
}

Then use it like:

html
<img class="w-full h-200">
container: { flex: 1, paddingTop: 50, paddingHorizontal: 20, }

Here's the equivalent styling using Tailwind CSS:

html
<div class="flex-1 pt-12 px-5">
  <!-- Your content here -->
</div>

Explanation:

  • flex-1: Sets the flex property to 1.
  • pt-12: Adds padding-top of 50px (12 * 4px = 48px, the closest to 50px in Tailwind's default spacing scale).
  • px-5: Adds horizontal padding of 20px (5 * 4px = 20px).

If you need exactly 50px for padding-top, you can add an inline style or extend Tailwind's configuration.

Using inline style:

html
<div class="flex-1 px-5" style="padding-top: 50px;">
  <!-- Your content here -->
</div>

Extending Tailwind configuration (tailwind.config.js):

js
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      padding: {
        '50': '50px',
      },
    },
  },
}

Then use it like:

html
<div class="flex-1 pt-50 px-5">
  <!-- Your content here -->
</div>
